\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Making sense of observed behavior of others in terms of unobservable mental
 traits is cognitive capacity essential for successful social interaction.
 Inferring what others might think, believe or intend helpsus navigate our
 complex social world.
 This sociocognitive capacity allows us to not just predict and understand
 the behavior of others based on their mental states, but also predict and
 understand how our behavior might affect the mental states of others.
 It is this capacity which allow self-aware humans to acknowledge and appreciate
 that others have mental states just like themselves.
 It has understandably been described as the pinnacle of social cognition
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "clayton "
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The capacity was originally referred to as 'theory of mind' in the seminal
 paper by Premack & Woodruff 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Premack & Woodruff"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in 1978.
 It has seen implicit philosophical attention for centuries and been of
 immense scientific interest in the last 40 years within studies such as
 psychology, biology, neuroscience and philosophy.
 This thesis consists of two parts: An article on an experiment, called
 the canteen dilemma, which aims at investigating the nature and limited
 use of theory of mind, as well as the present paper which works as an introduct
ion to the article.
 The canteen dilemma experiment was conducted at the Center for Information
 and Bubble studies and was designed and implemented in conjunction with
 R.
 Engelhardt and T.
 Bolander.
 The experiment consists of a two-player strategic coordination game with
 imperfect information with a structure such that one's social reasoning
 affects one's behavior in the game.
 The present introduction is intended to supplement the accompanying article
 by presenting and discussing relevant research on social cognition, how
 and why it is relevant to research in logic, as well as providing supplementary
 results and discussion on the canteen dilemma experiment itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is necessary to preface some of the discussion on social cognition with
 some reservations.
 The field has been criticized in terms of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

theory of mind
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 being used vaguely and inconsistently between studies and by reference
 to studies (i) treating theory of mind as a monolithic process, (ii) referring
 to a single brain network for theory of mind and (iii) conflating varieties
 of theory of mind 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schaafsma deconstructing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It has also been argued that certain studies which point to cases of theory
 of mind could be explained without reference to mental states 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heyes submentalizing"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 This calls for a critical assessment of the scientific understanding of
 theory of mind which will be discussed later in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Limitations-to-theconcept"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Attributing mental states to others have also been referred to as 'mentalizing'
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heyes submentalizing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 'mind-reading' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heyes cultural evolution"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 'perspective taking' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "perspective taking"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 'higher-order social cognition/reasoning' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "social intelligence,verbrugge logic and social cognition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Given that the canteen dilemma's emphasis on reasoning about possible mental
 states of others in order to inform one's decisions, I will often use the
 term higher-order social reasoning or cognition, including the term 'social'
 to emphasize interpersonal aspect involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite methodological difficulties, the ability to attribute mental states
 to others is undeniably both real and important.
 This ability allows us to develop a more complete and accurate understanding
 of those around us and as such is an essential part of understanding what
 it means to be human.
 The reasoning involved can be applied recursively, modeling the mental
 state of others, including their model of one's own mental state, and so
 on.
 The recursive modeling of the mental states of others is referred to as
 higher-order social reasoning or cognition and it is this cognitive activity
 that is the general focus of the canteen dilemma experiment and this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Epistemic logic, the modal logic of knowledge, is a logical language capable
 of representing the knowledge of agents in complex situations and as such
 is a natural tool for describing higher-order social reasoning.
 In general, zero-order reasoning concerns facts about the world, while
 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

-order reason concerns facts about 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-order reasoning of other people 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "verbrugge logic and social cognition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since higher order social reasoning can be described in various epistemic
 logics, the interface between logic and cognitive science has recently
 received interest.
 There is a two-fold question in this interdisciplinary field: To what extent
 do people reason differently from logical prescriptions and how do we interpret
 possible divergence in the two areas of research? The first question will
 be discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "sec:Higher-order-social"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 while the latter question will be discussed in the section below.
 After the following section I present the epistemic logic 
\begin_inset Formula $S5$
\end_inset

 before I turn to relevant empirical insights from cognitive science, focusing
 on the possible limits of human reasoning.
 This leads to a description of the canteen dilemma.
 As the essential details and results of the experiment are fleshed out
 in the accompanying article, this introduction will keep to discussion
 of supplementary results and analysis of the experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The cognitive turn in logic 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Logic-and-the"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logic bears a long but intricate relation to human reasoning.
 The logic of argumentation has been studied since antiquity and is still
 frequently taught to first year philosophy students.
 The goal of this is presumably not just to teach students about valid inference
s but also to improve the validity of inferences they make themselves.
 Modern logic has besides this traditionally been seen as unrelated to empirical
 facts about human reasoning except as a normative force of how we ought
 to make inferences.
 Modern logic has been undergoing a cognitive turn in recent years which
 has emphasized its relation to human reasoning, notably championed by logicians
 such as Johan van Benthem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "benthem facts matter"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Rineke Verbrugge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "verbrugge logic and social cognition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

This cognitive turn is a step away from the anti-psychologism exhibited
 in the early days of modern logic, as Frege stated that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

logic is concerned .
 .
 .
 not with the question of how people think, but with the question of how
 they must think if they are not to miss the truth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 250"
key "frege1897"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Frege refers to the normativity of logic but his point rests on a more
 fundamental claim that logic is the study of objective mind-independent
 logical laws, which he states explicitly: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the laws of truth are not psychological laws: they are boundary stones set
 in an eternal foundation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 13"
key "frege 1964"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 So logic is normative according to Frege because the norms for reasoning
 and beliefs are structured by what is truth-conducing and the laws of logic
 are objective truths, in fact necessary truths.
 Andersen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "neo-kantianism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues that Husserl followed Frege in this anti-psychologism as Husserl
 even argued that any argument that makes logic independent from psychology
 by reference to the distinction between how we ought to think and how do
 do think is implicitly psychologistic, since any such argument still refers
 to human reasoning (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "§17-20"
key "Husserl"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 So for Frege and Husserl, the normativity of logic is a side-effect of
 its objectivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objectivity of logic has been part of a fundamental philosophical debate
 about what makes logical truths true, what logical facts are about and
 whether they are necessarily or contingently true.
 There is a rich historical dialogue on this from Frege, Husserl, Wittgenstein,
 Ayer, Carnap, Quine, Kripke and Putnam among others, although its discussion
 is only indirectly related to how the purity of logic relates to the quirks
 of human reasoning.
 Assume we reject Frege's view and adopt a non-Platonistic Realism like
 Maddy  
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "maddy phil of logic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or even more radical empirical version from Quine 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Quine"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which states that the truth of logical laws are contingent on the right
 physical structuring.
 This does not affect the normativity of logic because even on such a view,
 human reasoning takes place within the physical structuring in question
 and is governed by the laws of logic as well.
 How is human reasoning relevant for logic then?
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take argumentative logic.
 There are certain inferences that humans make that can only be described
 as mistakes.
 Take Modus Ponens for example, from 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\rightarrow Q$
\end_inset

, we can conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, which can easily be relevant in situations where failing to infer 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 can have adverse consequences.
 But there are more complex cases which can be modeled by more complex logics
 and where deviance from the logical model might not be a mistake in reasoning.
 There are few reasons for this which both encourage collaboration between
 logic and cognitive science.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, if someone makes an inference which is invalid in classical logic,
 it does not follow that it is logically invalid in non-classical logics.
 There might be good reason for human reasoning does not always follow prescript
ions from classical logic, such as when dealing with incomplete information
 or limited cognitive resources.
 See Drew & Doyle 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nonmonotonic logic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Brewka 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "default reasoning"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for work on non-monotonic logic and default reasoning.
 Non-monotonic logic allows valid inferences on incomplete information for
 example such that new information might invalidate earlier inferences,
 which is not possible in classical logic.
 So, it does not follow that reasoning which deviates from some logical
 prescriptions is random or illogical.
 Such reasoning might simply not be properly formalized or represented.
 People might reason differently for various reasons and if logic wants
 to maintain its normativity, it should take these different reasoning patterns
 seriously.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, the problem of developing artificial intelligence was first described
 as that of “making a machine behave in ways that would be called intelligent
 if a human were so behaving
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by John McCarthy in 1956 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 11"
key "mccarthy ai"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 If we want machines to be able to reason similarly to humans, it is necessary
 to be know the logical structure of how humans actually reason.
 This is especially important when it comes to higher-order social cognition.
 If we want to be able to interact intelligently with artificial agents,
 such agents will have to be able to reason about and understand the reasoning
 of humans.
 In other words, if human reasoning deviates systematically from idealized
 logical prescriptions, AI systems should taking this into account when
 having to predict the behavior of humans.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

I will now turn to epistemic logic as an example of an idealized representation
 of reasoning about knowledge.
 Epistemic logic was originally used to formalize and analyze epistemological
 notions and concepts and is also useful as a tool for showing the epistemic
 depth of certain real world situations.
 Some relevant idealizations will be discussed before moving onto real higher-or
der social reasoning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\noindent
Epistemic logic 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Epistemic-logic--"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Epistemic logic is a useful modeling tool for representing complex epistemic
 components of real world cases.
 An epistemic language is defined below with a subsequent focus on the system
 
\begin_inset Formula $S5$
\end_inset

 as it is the most of often used to symbolize knowledge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definiton
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

1.1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(Epistemic
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

language)
\series default
 Let 
\emph on
P 
\emph default
be a set of atomic propositions and 
\emph on
A 
\emph default
a set of agent-symbols.
 The language 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L_{K}}$
\end_inset

 for multi-agent epistemic logic is then generated by the following BNF:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\Coloneqq p\,|\,\lnot\varphi\,|\,(\varphi\land\varphi)\,|\,K_{a}\varphi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Disjunction, conditional and bi-conditional can be used standardly as abbreviati
ons of formulas using the negation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\lnot$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, conjunction 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\land$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Kripke models and truth conditions are also defined for our epistemic language,
 before going into the art of modeling in epistemic logic, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition 1.2 (Kripke models) 
\series default
A 
\emph on
Kripke model 
\emph default
for the epistemic language is a structure 
\begin_inset Formula $M=(S,R,V)$
\end_inset

, where 
\emph on
S
\emph default
 is a set of states, 
\emph on
R 
\emph default
is an accessibility relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{a}\subseteq S\times S$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{a}st$
\end_inset

 means 
\emph on
t 
\emph default
is accessible from 
\emph on
s 
\emph default
for agent 
\emph on
a
\emph default
.
 
\emph on
V
\emph default
 is a valuation function assigning truth values to propositions at states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition 1.3 (Truth conditions) 
\series default
Epistemic formulas are interpreted on 
\emph on
pointed models 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $M,s$
\end_inset

 consisting of a Kripke model 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

and a state 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Truth conditions for formulas are then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\vDash p$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 true at 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\vDash\lnot\varphi$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $not$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\vDash\varphi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\vDash\varphi\land\psi$
\end_inset

 iff  
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\vDash\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\vDash\psi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\vDash K_{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $for\,all\,worlds\,t\,such\,that\,R_{a}st,\,M,t\vDash\varphi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will focus on the prominent epistemic logic 
\begin_inset Formula $S5$
\end_inset

, which is the set of Kripke models where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
 I will also use 
\emph on
states
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
worlds
\emph default
 interchangeably.
 We get 
\begin_inset Formula $S5$
\end_inset

 by adding the following axiom schema to our logic (which can both be understood
 in terms of their epistemic consequences and the implication for the accessibil
ity relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $K_{a}\varphi\rightarrow\varphi$
\end_inset

 (truth or reflexivity),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $K_{a}\varphi\rightarrow K_{a}K_{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 (positive introspection or transitivity) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot K_{a}\varphi\rightarrow K_{a}\lnot K_{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 (negative introspection or euclidity)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first axiom entails veridicality and is mostly uncontroversial: if you
 know something, it is true.
 The other two implies that agents are aware of what they know and do not
 know, which are both often referred to as psychologically unrealistic idealizat
ions.
 I later discuss other and more important idealizations in epistemic logic.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S5$
\end_inset

 allows 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to be interpreted as an 
\emph on
indistinguishability
\emph default
 relation.
 This entails that agents do not which of the worlds they consider possible
 is the actual one.
 It intuitively encapsulates the semantics above, which state that agents
 only know something when it is the case in all worlds they consider possible.
 We can also add a modal operator for 
\emph on
mutual knowledge, 
\emph default
symbolizing that every agent in group 
\emph on
B
\emph default
 knows 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, namely 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $E_{B}\varphi$
\end_inset


\series default
, defined as the conjunction of all individuals in 
\emph on
B 
\emph default
knowing 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 That is, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq A$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $E_{B}\varphi=\underset{b\in B}{\bigwedge}K_{b}\varphi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the limiting case of the infinite conjunction mutual knowledge, where
 everyone knows 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, and everyone knows that everyone knows 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
ad infinitum
\emph default
, we introduce the notion of 
\emph on
common knowledge
\emph default
:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $C_{B}\varphi=\stackrel[n=0]{\infty}{\bigwedge}E_{B}^{n}\varphi$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Common knowledge is interpreted semantically such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is common knowledge among a group 
\emph on
A 
\emph default
in a state 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 if and only if, for all worlds 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in the reflexive transitive closure of the accessibility relations for
 all agents in 
\emph on
A
\emph default
, 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
holds in
\emph on
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\emph default
.
 There is an intriguing but unintuitive difference between any finite number
 of iterations of the 
\emph on
E-
\emph default
operator and the infinite iteration expressed in common knowledge.
 The difference can be made explicit in examples from epistemic logic like
 the 'consecutive numbers' example below.
 This example is structured very similarly to the canteen dilemma as we
 will see later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Consecutive-numbers-example "

\end_inset

 Consecutive numbers example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:-Consecutive-numbers"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two agents 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
(Anne) and 
\emph on
b 
\emph default
(Bill) sit together.
 They are told they will each receive a natural number and that their numbers
 will be consecutive such that the numbers are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 They are only told told their own number but it is common knowledge between
 Anne and Bill that their numbers are consecutive.
 This entails a structure where in any given situation, each agent know
 their own number and considers it possible that the other agent has a number
 one before or after (unless they have 0)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The following example is based on the consecutive numbers example in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "consecutive numbers book"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DEL"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 
\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename consecutive numbers diagram1.png
	scale 60

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\series bold

\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consecutive numbers model (Ditmarsch & Kooi 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "consecutive numbers book"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the real situation is Anne being told 2 and Bill 3, denoted as a
 state 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

.
 There are a few basic facts which are true in 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

.
 Most basically, Anne knows her number is 2 and Bill knows his number is
 3: 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{a}a_{2}\land K_{b}b_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Since they know their numbers are consecutive, they both know that there
 are only two possible numbers for the other (but these are not the same
 for Anne and Bill!): 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{a}(b_{1}\lor b_{3})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{b}(a_{2}\lor a_{4})$
\end_inset

.
 Since Anne considers it possible that Bill has as 1 or 3, she considers
 it possible that Bill considers 0 or 2 possible for Anne (if Bill has 1)
 or 2 or 4 (if Bill has 3), stated as: 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{a}(K_{b}(a_{0}\lor a_{2})\lor(K_{b}(a_{2}\lor a_{2}))$
\end_inset

.
 Now imagine that Anne and Bill has to guess whether they both have positive
 numbers, that is, none of them have a 0, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $(positive)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we ask Anne and Bill in state 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

 if they know that the other's number is positive, they would both answer
 yes: 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{a}(positive)\land K_{b}(positive)$
\end_inset

 or expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\{a,b\}}(positive)$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to checking for each agent 
\emph on
i 
\emph default
whether every world which is
\emph on
 i
\emph default
-accessible from 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

 only has positive numbers.
 However, now imagine that we ask both Anne and Bill if they both know that
 
\begin_inset Formula $(positive)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 Bill considers 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(4,3)$
\end_inset

 possible.
 Since we are only focused on 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, we can focus on the lowest number-pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

, since the other direction only takes us away from 0.
 Bill knows Anne's lowest possible number is 2 , which means he knows both
 numbers are positive.
 Since if Anne has a 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, she would consider 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as the lowest number, Bill knows that Anne knows both numbers are positive
 as well: 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{b}K_{a}(positive)$
\end_inset

.
 But even though Anne in fact has a 2, meaning she knows that both numbers
 are positive since the lowest possible number for Bill would be 1, if Bill
 has a 1, he considers it possible that Anne as a 0.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot K_{a}K_{b}(positive).$
\end_inset

 In other words, while everyone knows that no one has a 0, not everyone
 knows this epistemic fact itself: 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\{a,b\}}(positive)\land\lnot E_{\{a,b\}}E_{\{a,b\}}(positive)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

The unintuitive aspect of this is the satisfaction of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 iterations of the 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 operator but not 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset


\emph default
.
 So in the consecutive number example, no matter what number pair Anne and
 Bill are given, it is never common knowledge that none of them have a 0!
 This also means that telling Anne and Bill that both of their numbers are
 positive is actually an informative statement in any possible situation
 of the consecutive numbers example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The practical implications of this can be seen by 'gamifying' the example.
 Imagine Anne and Bill have to answer independently of each other whether
 they are certain that both have positive numbers or remain agnostic.
 Their objective is to (1) always give the same answer and (2) not answering
 they have positive numbers if they do not.
 In our supposed case 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

, both agents know they both have positive numbers.
 But as established above, Anne does not know that Bill knows.
 So Anne might remain agnostic and since Bill knows that Anne might have
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, suppose he chooses to do the same.
 This line of reasoning generalizes to any natural number pair in the consecutiv
e number game just devised.
 The reasoning becomes less intuitive as the numbers go up, since it depend
 on increasing orders of social reasoning.
 For example if two real people were given 
\begin_inset Formula $719$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $720$
\end_inset

 in a structure as above and asked the same question, they would probably
 agree that they are certain about it.
 In fact, they might be hard to dissuade otherwise because remaining agnostic
 relies on higher-order social reasoning out of cognitive reach for normal
 people.
 Reasoning about the possible number of the other depends on zero-order
 reasoning, while reasoning about what numbers the other considers possible
 is first-order, and so on as iterations continue.
 As we will see in a few sections, adults are often said to be limited to
 second-order reasoning at most, implying that while Anne and Bill would
 remain agnostic in state 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

, they might answer differently in 
\begin_inset Formula $(3,4)$
\end_inset

, since Anne would remain agnostic due to second-order reasoning, while
 Bill would not since it would rely on third-order reasoning.
 The next section focuses on some of the details of the limitation on social
 cognition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Higher order social reasoning in real life
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Higher-order-social"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Limitations-to-theconcept"

\end_inset

Limitations to the concept of theory of mind
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the term 'theory of mind' have been used in various different ways,
 some conceptual clarification is in order.
 As mentioned above, the term sometimes conflates varieties of cognitive
 capacities and the general cognitive capacity to represent the mental states
 of others have also been called various different terms.
 Research in economics often refer to higher-order rationality
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "higherorder rationality"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or reasoning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "higher order reasoning 2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 since equilibrium models of game theory depend on higher order beliefs,
 while other fields often focus more on mental terms.
 Some researchers like Schaafsma et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schaafsma deconstructing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have called for a reformulation of the term 'theory of mind' due to its
 heterogeneous usage.
 This includes deconstructing it into basic processes before reconstructing
 a scientifically tractable concept of theory of mind.
 While a proper reconstruction of the theory of mind concept is outside
 the scope of this thesis, it is necessary to understand some of the heterogenei
ty of its use and meaning in order to avoid unnecessary confusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, there is a debate about whether social reasoning constitutes a 
\emph on
theory
\emph default
, implying it is a cognitive process similar to that of constructing a scientifi
c theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gopnik theory theory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, or whether it is a more of an automatic intuitive process of 
\emph on
simulating 
\emph default
the mental state of someone else 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "simulation theory,simulation theory hurley,simulation theory 2 hurley"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This distinction is also somewhat reflected in studies distinguishing between
 reflective and spontaneous social cognition.
 Verbrugge & Mol 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Verbrugge 2008,verbrugge logic and social cognition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that there is a relevant gap between adults reflective understanding
 of theory of mind and its application in games.
 The distinction between reflective and spontaneous social cognition is
 mirrored in the debate about explicit and implicit social reasoning.
 According to Heyes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heyes submentalizing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, implicit mentalizing involves thinking about mental states in a fast,
 automatic way whereas explicit mentalizing is done in a slow and controlled
 way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, there is a debate about 
\emph on
nativist 
\emph default
and 
\emph on
constructionist
\emph default
 accounts of theory of mind.
 The nativist account assumes that the capacity to represent the mental
 states of others depends on dedicated cognitive processes which have been
 uniquely developed through human evolution for its purpose 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heyes submentalizing,nativist account"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The constructionist, or developmental account, assumes this mental capacity
 to be learned and culturally inherited 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heyes submentalizing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to critically evaluate the concept of theory of mind since
 the conceptual nomenclature we use can affect our understanding of the
 actual mental capacity.
 Heyes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heyes submentalizing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for example argues that a lot of studies referring to implicit mentalizing
 can be explained by what she calls submentalizing, a cognitive mechanism
 which simulates the effects of mentalizing in social contexts.
 Bloom & German 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bloom and germany abandon false belief"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also present two reasons why the standard false belief task is not suitable
 for testing theory of mind.
 First, passing the false belief task requires other cognitive capacities
 than just a theory of mind, like general task demands, which causes young
 children to fail regardless of any theory of mind.
 Second, having a theory of mind involves more than the ability to reason
 about false beliefs.
 That is, even though children younger than 2 years fail the false belief
 task, studies show that they can still appreciate some of the mental states
 of others, like attributing goals to others 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Csibra"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 So besides the different terminology used, the capacity of attributing
 mental states to others is possible a complex made up of various cognitive
 processes, which would plausibly explain the heterogeneity of the methods
 used to test it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next section is a discussion on how people diverge from logical prescription
s, particularly those from epistemic logic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Idealizations and imperfect reasoning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People never reason perfectly but the extent to which people's reasoning
 is flawed is subject to debate.
 The Wason selection task 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wason 1966,wason 1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was an early experiment showing limitations of zero-order reasoning.
 In Wason's study, subjects were shown sixteen cards with a letter on one
 side and a number on the other.
 Four of these, D, K, 3 and 7 were used.
 Subjects were then asked which cards to turn in order to evaluate whether
 the following claim was true: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Every card which has a D on one side has a 3 on the other
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The claim has the structure of the material conditional 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow q$
\end_inset

.
 The correct cards to turn are those with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot q$
\end_inset

 but this answer (D and 7) was only the fourth most popular answer, while
 the most popular answer was D and 3, which includes the logical fallacy
 of affirming the consequent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such results seem to imply that humans are poor logical reasoners.
 But there are a few complexities.
 First off, Wason also found that people were significantly better at answering
 correctly when the question was about cities and transportation devices,
 specifically framed as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

every time I go to Manchester I travel by car
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Griggs & Cox 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "griggs"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also show that subjects perform near perfectly if the cards include ages
 and beverages and the claim 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph default
if a person is drinking beer, then that person is over 19 years old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 There is a long discussion on the thematic effect on the Wason selection
 task.
 One of the reasons for the different performance is arguably that the different
 thematic presentations warrants different interpretations.
 Stenning and van Lambalgen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stenning on wason"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that the abstract claim might be interpreted as merely checking satisfact
ion of instances instead of determining the truth of the rule.
 Wagner-Egger 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wagner_egger"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues that the 'error' made by most people may be due to interpreting
 the rule as a biconditional.
 The ambiguity of the statement could also explain why Cheng et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cheng on wason"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that people may even continue to do poorly after an introductory logic
 class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While this shows that there might be a non-deficiency explanation even when
 people seem to fail to make correct inferences in propositional logic,
 the fact still stands that people of course do not always reason perfectly.
 However traditional propositional logic often sets a standard that is low
 enough that it can be met at least in specialized settings where there
 is a special requirement to avoid logical failures.
 So propositional logic might not be overly idealized when it comes to arguments
 (ignoring the fact that propositional logic does not capture the dynamic
 and rhetorical aspects of real arguments).
 It is another story when it comes to higher order social reasoning.
 Before I go into empirical results on higher order social reasoning, let
 us look at some of the overly idealized aspects of 
\begin_inset Formula $S5$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Idealizations in epistemic logic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $S5$
\end_inset

 imply that agents are agents know all logical truths.
 Transitivity 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $(K_{a}\varphi\rightarrow K_{a}K_{a}\varphi)$
\end_inset

 and euclidity 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lnot K_{a}\varphi\rightarrow K_{a}\lnot K_{a}\varphi)$
\end_inset

 implies that agents have unlimited introspection of their own epistemic
 states, that is, they have a perfect account of what they know and do not
 know.
 But there are other idealizations which are less discussed
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
.
 To see this, note that real knowledge is gathered in a dynamic social environme
nt, where agents update and change their knowledge and beliefs as they gain
 new information.
 There are many aspects of the social dynamics of knowledge which are outside
 the scope of this thesis, but some of this dynamic can be expressed by
 our epistemic logic by adding action expressions as well as dynamic modalities
 for these.
 This means adding the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $[!\varphi]\varphi$
\end_inset

, with the truth condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\models[!\varphi]\psi$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $M,s\models\varphi$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $M|\varphi,s\models\psi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is often mentioned that public announcement of an atomic fact makes it
 common knowledge, while the same is not always the case for epistemic facts.
 Statements like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
p 
\emph default
is true but you don't know it
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Moore-type
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sentences which leads to unsuccessful updates.
 But when announcing non-epistemic propositions, agents 
\emph on
ought
\emph default
 to come to know it.
 This rests however on the idealized presupposition that agents have perfect
 observation, since the announcement and its contents must be clearly understood
 by all, and perfect recall, since agents must be able to remember all of
 this as time passes.
 In fact, for an announcement to become common knowledge, perfect observation
 and recall must be common knowledge among agents as well.
 Publicly announcing non-epistemic facts to real people do not always bring
 about common knowledge about such facts.
 Statements can either be too complex or lengthy for agents to decipher,
 or the statements might be ambiguous, as some researchers argue in the
 Wason selection task.
 In other words, if the mistakes in the Wason selection has to be put in
 terms of cognitive limits, they might not indicate a limit in computational
 power but rather a limit in observational power.
 As we will see later, limitations in terms of social cognition does not
 seem to occur due to limited zero-order reasoning, it is rather some barrier
 to the modal depth of formulas agents can come to know.
 The next section gives a brief overview of such parameters for cognitive
 limitations as found in Liu 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Liu diversity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Following this is a discussion on empirical findings regarding higher order
 social cognition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Parameters for diverse cognitive capacities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fenrong Liu identifies five novel parameters for diversity among epistemic
 agents 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 25f"
key "Liu diversity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\noindent
(a) Inferential or computational power: making valid inferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\noindent
(b) Introspection: being aware of one's own knowledge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\noindent
(c) Observation: correctly observing current events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\noindent
(d) Memory: capacity to remember observed events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\noindent
(e) Revision policies: varying from conservative to radical revision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Parameters (a) to (d) can be understood as logical norms describing the
 limits of truth-conducing capacities.
 That is, even if no one is perfect, each parameter is a way in which agents
 could be epistemically better off.
 This is difficult to see with (e) however, where the optimal case is not
 clear, since neither complete epistemic conservatism or revisionism seems
 rational.
 As Liu writes, it might be better to move away from understanding deviations
 from such norms purely negatively as 'limits' or 'bounds' on cognitive
 capacity, and instead see them positively as the different resources that
 agents have and use to successfully accomplish difficult tasks.
 After all, the story of humanity is largely a success story dependent on
 our cognitive prowess, even if so limited.
 As Benthem mentions, paraphrasing Joerg Siekmann, the most admirable in
 a mathematics seminar is not presenting a well-oiled proof, it is rather
 the ability to discover a mistake and recover on the spot.
 Rationality on this view is owed to learning from one's mistakes, and as
 Benthem points out, the dynamic behavior involved in this surely depends
 on more mechanisms than just inferences.
 This is just to present an alternative picture of discussion on cognitive
 limitations which are not simply deficit-based.
 I will now present and discuss some empirical results concerning higher
 order social cognition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The development and importance of theory of mind
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Studies indicate that children learn to distinguish their own beliefs from
 others between the ages of 3 and 5 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wimmer"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, while children learn to make correct second-order attributions between
 age 6 to 8 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Perner"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Chandler et al.
 and Leslie 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chandler,Leslie 2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that sociocognitive processes are present even earlier and Csibra
 et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Csibra"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 even argue that basic theory of mind aspects as goal perception are present
 already in 9 to 12-month-old infants.
 Adults are generally limited to no more than second-order social reasoning,
 even though there is evidence that adults can rely on third and fourth-order
 reasoning in games when playing against programmed opponents which they
 know to rely on specific higher-order social reasoning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "veltman training use of theory of mind"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Before discussing the limitations of higher-order social cognition even
 in adults, I will briefly motivate why it is important to understand such
 sociocognitive limitations.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before moving onto specific limitations, it is important to note why such
 limitations are relevant.
 Having an insight into the mental workings of others play a vital role
 in both social interaction and basic human functions such as having empathy
 towards others 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "empathy 1,Empathy2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There two other general reasons why it is important to map apparent limitations
 of this vital mental capacity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we can only hope to counteract and adjust for possible cognitive
 shortcomings if we become aware of them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, even when higher-order reasoning deviates from certain logical prescript
ions it is not necessarily a logical mistake in the sense that the reasoning
 might simply fits some other logical framework.
 People interact and cooperate successfully with others all the time, so
 if social reasoning is limited, there must be other heuristics that take
 over.
 Finding out how reasoning is limited relative to logical frameworks makes
 it possible to figure out what such alternative heuristics might be.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, ambient technology such as self-driving cars have to understand
 and predict human actions, and as such have to reason about how humans
 might reason.
 Such artificial agents would be wrong to assume that humans reasons like
 themselves.
 In fact, as Benjamin Erb 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Erb - AI and ToM"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues, when optimizing intelligent human-computer interaction it is important
 that both humans and their non-human counterparts can reason about the
 'mental' states of each other.
 That is, for non-human agents to successfully predict and reason about
 the behavior of humans, they will have to simulate human beliefs and the
 usefulness of such a simulation hinges on how accurately the it represents
 the actual mental state of the human in question.
 Since the only salient factor here is accuracy of representation, questions
 of normativity can be ignored.
 This also holds the other way around, as Erb writes: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

In intelligent, technical environments, humans may intrinsically apply ToM
 traits to their non-human interaction partners
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Humans may in other words also attribute a 'mental' model to non-human
 interaction partners concerning the reasoning and intentions behind their
 actions.
 This leads to some of various limitations of human social cognition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The difficulty of reading minds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several different ways in which human cognition seems to be limited
 in terms of higher order social reasoning.
 It is limited in the sense that it is seemingly capped at first or second-order
 reasoning.
 Studies show that most adults in game-like settings can utilize first-order
 reasoning and do a good attempt at second-order reasoning, while having
 a higher order theory of mind is rare 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Flobbeverbrugge etc 2008,hedden2002,Verbrugge 2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There are signs of more severe limitations however, indicating that social
 reasoning is either entirely absent or otherwise incomplete in ways which
 are not encapsulated by simply being restricted to a certain order of social
 reasoning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Spontaneous versus reflective use of theory of mind
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimental studies show that there is a relevant difference between having
 a capacity to correctly attribute mental states to others and actually
 using this in practice.
 Keysar et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Keysar 2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that there is a stark dissociation between having the ability to
 reflectively distinguish one's beliefs from others and the routine deployment
 of this ability in interpreting the actions of others.
 Their findings imply that even adults who are capable of forming reasonable
 beliefs about the beliefs of others do not consult this crucial knowledge
 when interpreting the actions of others.
 Their claim is specific to the capacity of representing beliefs of others
 separately from corresponding reality, that is, acknowledging that others
 might have false beliefs.
 It suggests a difference between relying on one's theory of mind in reflective
 tasks and utilizing as a decision-guiding mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Flobbe et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Flobbeverbrugge etc 2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also show examples of children who could understand second-order reasoning
 in story tasks while failing to properly perform second order reasoning
 in game tasks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Curse of Knowledge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Birch & Bloom 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bloom"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that adults who have to attribute beliefs to others have a tendency
 to attribute their own belief instead of correctly attributing a false
 belief.
 They write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

adult's own knowledge of an event's outcome can compromise their ability
 to reason about another person's beliefs about that event
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 College aged adults were told a story where a girl Vicky puts her violin
 in a blue container.
 While Vicky is outside, her sister Denise puts the violin in a different
 container, depending on the treatment, either (Ignorance) simply in another
 container, (plausible knowledge) moves violin to the red container or (implausi
ble knowledge) moves the violin to the purple container.
 The plausibly and implausible condition relates to the red container being
 violin shaped, while the purple container being an odd shape for a violin.
 When subjects did not know where the violin had been moved, they where
 generally good at predicting that Vicky would look for her violin in the
 blue container.
 When the violin was moved to either the purple or the red container, participan
ts assigned significantly higher probabilities to Vicky looking in the purple
 or the red container respectively (even though Vicky would still believe
 it was in the blue container).
 Participants also assigned higher probabilities to the treatment with the
 red (plausible) container than with the blue (implausible) one.
 That is, participants relied on their own beliefs when attributing beliefs
 to Vicky, and this erroneous first-order social reasoning was strengthened
 by feeling more justified in their belief.
 The authors call this the the curse of knowledge and is related to the
 problem in Keysar et al.
 as well.
 Both show that theory of mind use might be task dependent, which we will
 look at now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Task dependence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The limitations described above suggest that successful application of theory
 of mind can be task-dependent, successfully applied in some contexts but
 not in others.
 Understanding why this ability might be task dependent can lead to better
 understanding the nature of higher order social cognition.
 Verbrugge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "verbrugge logic and social cognition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 lists a few possible explanations.
 First, there might be a high processing cost associated with theory of
 mind, causing a failure in applying appropriate order of social reasoning
 when the the processing cost becomes too high.
 Second, the capacity for performing higher order social reasoning does
 not necessarily transfer between domains.
 Being apple to apply this cognitive capacity across domains might require
 a development process like Representational Redescription to take place
 as suggested by Karmiloff-Smith 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Karmiloff"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Third, in order to utilize a higher order theory of mind in a situation,
 it is not just necessary to possess this capacity, but also to recognize
 that it is advantageous to incorporate this knowledge into actions, decisions
 or interpretation of the actions of others.
 This is in line with the explanation that applying higher order social
 reasoning has a high processing cost.
 In other words, due to the high processing cost of applying it, it might
 simply not be worth the effort to rely on it per default, so it might largely
 be ignored until its importance becomes sufficiently apparent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is further supported by an argument in Keysar et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Keysar 2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as to why adults do not always deploy their existing theory of mind.
 They mention that in the real word, perspectives often tend to coincide.
 This means that a lot of knowledge important for social interaction is
 common knowledge, which reinforces the point above that differentiating
 between one's beliefs and the beliefs of others might unnecessarily take
 up cognitive resources.
 As Keysar et al.
 mentions, the dynamic nature of face-to-face interactions give people a
 feedback mechanism which allows them to be egocentric by effectively distributi
ng the burden of applying appropriate order social reasoning across interlocutor
s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly, theory of mind might not be a uniform of social cognition at all.
 Without taking a complete behaviorist stance, one might even question to
 what extend theory of mind relates to mental states at all.
 It is possible that when researchers deduce implicit social reasoning,
 it might just be learned behavior.
 For example when a person hears a cyclist ring their bell they likely infer
 an intention behind the action, that the person doing it is impatient.
 But this is could perhaps be explained by simple learned behavior.
 It is also likely inferred so spontaneously that it does not seem right
 to say that people hear the sound and then reason about what it might mean.
 In phenomenological terms, the ringing of the bell might 
\emph on
sound
\emph default
 like someone is trying to get a reaction from you, which prompts the reaction
 without much explicit consideration of underlying mental states.
 If social reasoning is computationally 'expensive', this could explain
 how it can appear so extensively in everyday interaction, but also why
 it is difficult in more complex situations, since people might rarely be
 aware of the explicit use of their higher order theory of mind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This concludes the introduction to different logical and empirical aspects
 of higher order social cognition which underlies the canteen dilemma.
 Logical prescriptions often help us navigating how humans ought to reason,
 but as we have seen, in order to make prescriptive norms for higher order
 social reasoning, it is necessary to look at the actual reasoning done
 by real people.
 This leads us to the canteen dilemma, an experiment on coordination with
 imperfect information which involve exactly this type of reasoning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Canteen Dilemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canteen dilemma was devised by Thomas Bolander and designed and implemented
 in conjunction with Robin Engelhardt and myself.
 The game has structural affinity to the consecutive number example in section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Consecutive-numbers-example "
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 It likewise depicts a situation where two agents have mutual knowledge
 about something iterated several times (everyone knows that, everyone knows
 that ...) while never having common knowledge (everyone knows that, everyone
 knows that ...
 infinitely iterated).
 The structure is framed in a thematic story since studies show that this
 can significantly improve people's zero-order logical reasoning abilities
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Meijering,wason 1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and this reasoning is not the focus of the canteen dilemma.
 The story is the following: Each player is told that they and their colleague
 arrive for work every morning between 8:00 am and 9:10 am.
 They always arrive 10 minutes apart but only know their own arrival time.
 The task for the players is to coordinate their decisions, while knowing
 that both have to go to the office if they arrive at 9:00 or later.
 Their preferences are ordered such that their prefer (1) going to the canteen
 together if both arrive before 9:00, (2) going to the office together at
 any time and (3) all other configurations, that is, discoordinating or
 either player going to the canteen at 9:00 or later.
 The game consists of a number of rounds where each player are assigned
 an arrival time and have to decide between going to the canteen or the
 office.
 The payoff structure follows a logarithmic scoring rule, meaning participants
 gave an estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of how certain they were that they made the right choice, implicitly assigning
 
\begin_inset Formula $100-p$
\end_inset

 to being wrong.
 Research on eliciting belief have shown that forecasts from observers through
 proper scoring rules are significantly more accurate and calibrated
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Calibrated is defined as: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a set of probabilistic predictions are 
\emph on
calibrated
\emph default
 if 
\emph on
p
\emph default
 percent of all predictions reported at probability 
\emph on
p
\emph default
 are true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Seidenfeld"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 than those elicited using improper scoring rules 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Seidenfeld"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Players were shown all previous results after each round, including the
 previous arrival times and choices of both players and their payoffs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rules dictate that players prefer going to the canteen if they both
 arrive before 9:00, but that they should always go to the office if they
 or their colleague arrives at 9:00 or 9:10.
 Take the following example to see some of the complexity of the game.
 Assume player 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
arrives at 8:50.
 Player 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
know that 
\emph on
b
\emph default
 arrived at 8:40 or 9:00.
 If 
\emph on
b
\emph default
 arrived at 9:00, 
\emph on
a
\emph default
 should go to the office.
 If
\emph on
 b
\emph default
 arrived at 8:40, they would prefer going to the canteen together.
 Player 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
knows they prefer going to the canteen but since one of the possible scenarios
 would require her to go to the office assume player 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
chooses the office at 8:50.
 Now assume 
\emph on
a
\emph default
 arrives at 8:40 instead and reasons the following way.
 If 
\emph on
b 
\emph default
arrives at 8:50 am and reasons like 
\emph on
a, 
\emph default
player 
\emph on
b
\emph default
 they would go to the office at 8:50 as well, in which case 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
might go to the office at 8:40 just like they did at 8:50.
 This line of reasoning follows for all possible arrival times by backwards
 induction, and so 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
might never choose to go to the canteen! 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that a player who arrives at 8:40 knows that the other arrived at
 8:50 at the latest and that it is therefore preferable for both to go to
 the canteen.
 However, players do not just have to consider the possible arrival times,
 they also have to consider what others might do in such circumstances.
 In order to predict the choice the other player might make in their situation,
 the first player has to consider what the other player considers possible,
 which is different from their own point of view.
 That is, the player who arrives at 8:40 has to appreciate the fact that
 while she knows that both would prefer going to the canteen, the other
 player does not know this.
 So making an office choice at 8:40 or earlier requires a player to not
 just consider facts about the world, that is, if both arrived before 9:00
 or not, but also consider what the other player would do in this situation,
 which depends on the beliefs of the other player.
 This means that predicting an office choice at 8:40 or earlier relies on
 higher order social reasoning.
 Of course, players can always choose office for whatever reason, for example
 if they just make random choices.
 But we would expect this to be both evenly distributed among both canteen
 and office choices as well as across arrival times.
 This means that the relative difference can still be indicative of reasoning
 of participants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice however the premise above that for 
\emph on
a
\emph default
 to go to the office at 8:40, she has to consider how 
\emph on
b 
\emph default
reasons if she arrived at 8:50.
 It means that 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
assumes 
\emph on
b 
\emph default
to reason like herself
\emph on
.
 
\emph default
So this example does not just assume that 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
performs first-order social reasoning but also that she believes 
\emph on
b 
\emph default
to correctly apply zero-order reasoning to reach a specific conclusion.
 So it does not just rely on players reasoning a specific way but also that
 it is common knowledge among players that they reason a specific way.
 This means that regardless of what player 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
thinks 
\emph on
b 
\emph default
ought to do, 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
has to try and to figure out what 
\emph on
b 
\emph default
will actually do.
 It implies that without common knowledge about rationality, two rational
 players cannot be expected to play rationally.
 They might both choose canteen because they do not believe the other to
 apply the sufficient order of social reasoning, or that the other believes
 that they do and so on.
 While office choices arguably does signify social reasoning, choosing canteen
 does therefore not signify a lack of it.
 To summarize, I postulate towo conditionals: 
\series bold
(1) 
\series default
If a participant chooses office at 8:40 or earlier, they rely on higher-order
 social reasoning and (2) if a participant only uses zero-order reasoning,
 they will choose canteen at 8:40 and earlier, office at 9:00 and later
 and 8:50 being a toss up.
 I argue that choosing office at 8:50 does not necessarily rely on first-order
 social reasoning, since it is a fact about the world stated in the rules
 that the other might arrive at 9:00 and that you should choose office in
 that case.
 The converse conditionals are not taken to be true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

The certainty estimates involved can be valuable to get further information
 here.
 Assume a rational player plays the game and arrives at 8:40.
 They might infer that the optimal choice would be going to the office by
 relying on higher order social reasoning, assuming the other thinks the
 same way.
 But if they are uncertain about what type of reasoner the other player
 is, they might believe that the other player might play canteen and they
 can therefore hedge their decision by being less certain.
 So the certainty estimates helps offset some of the loss of possible discoordin
ation if it can be predicted.
 This makes it possible to distinguish between players who all choose canteen
 at a given arrival time, since those who assign a lower certainty estimate
 to it than others implicitly assign a higher chance to office and therefore
 make use of higher-order of social reasoning per (1) above.
 This also help deflect what Verbrugge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "verbrugge logic and social cognition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 calls the danger of simplistic formal systems which posit fixed bounds
 on social cognition, that is, assuming that people can reason up to 
\emph on
n 
\emph default
order but not 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph default
This will also be the focus when viewing the results later, since it shows
 that natural social cognition might be more continuous than previously
 described.
 Before looking into the results, I will now go through some of the logical
 structure of the game in terms of epistemic logic.
 This is followed by supplementary discussion and results of the canteen
 dilemma not included in the accompanying article.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Logical structure of the canteen dilemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the canteen dilemma has a logical structure similar to the consecutive
 numbers example in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:-Consecutive-numbers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it can be represented in a similar diagram.
 Note that a situation like (8:00, 8:10) denotes that agent 
\emph on
a 
\emph default
arrived at 8:00 and 
\emph on
b 
\emph default
arrived at 8:10.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
